        "excerpt": "I have come into my garden, my sister, my bride... Eat, friends; drink and imbibe deeply, O lovers.",
        "body": "Verse 1 is simultaneously the closing line of chapter 4's argument and the prologue to chapter 5's crisis. The beloved announces his arrival in the perfect tense — five completed actions: *come, gathered, eaten, drunk* — establishing that his entry into the garden (invited by the bride at 4:16) is a fact, not a wish. The garden he enters is laden with the same aromatic vocabulary that characterized the bride throughout chapter 4: myrrh, balsam, honeycomb, honey, wine, milk. He has not arrived to an empty place; he has arrived to the fullness the bride embodied.\n\nThe verse's most theologically striking element is its close: *Eat, friends; drink and imbibe deeply, O lovers.* The beloved does not keep the garden's feast for himself and the bride alone; he opens it to the gathered community. *Rea* (friends) and *dod* (lovers) appear here as a pair — the wider circle of those who share in the love being celebrated. Whether these are wedding guests, the daughters of Jerusalem, or a chorus of well-wishers, their inclusion signals that covenant love is not a closed circuit. It produces abundance that overflows.\n\nThis verse sets an ironic backdrop for the door-scene that follows. The beloved has already entered, already feasted, already invited others to the table — and then he finds himself outside the door of the bedroom, knocking in the cold. The bride who issued the invitation of 4:16 is now the one who is not ready to receive him. The movement from 5:1 to 5:2 is the chapter's first and deepest irony.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gan* (garden) is the same word used in Genesis 2:8 for the garden of Eden — its appearance throughout the Song (4:12, 15, 16; 5:1; 6:2) carries Edenic resonance: intimacy without shame in a space of creaturely abundance. *Shakhar* (imbibe deeply, drink freely) suggests satiation to the point of exhilaration — the feast is not meager."
