        "title": "The knocking that goes unanswered — hesitation and its irreversible cost (5:2-6)",
        "range": "5:2-6",
        "excerpt": "A voice! My beloved was knocking: 'Open to me, my sister, my darling, my dove, my perfect one!' ... I opened to my beloved, but my beloved had turned away and had gone.",
        "body": "The scene opens with the Hebrew exclamatory *qol!* — 'A voice! A sound!' — which crashes into the narrative without introduction. The bride's sleeping-but-awake state (5:2) is one of the Song's most psychologically precise images: she is not fully absent from him, but she is not fully present either. The heart wakes before the body; she hears him before she responds to him. This is not indifference but inertia — the posture of one who loves but is not urgently attentive.\n\nThe beloved's fourfold address in 5:2 is the most concentrated string of endearments in the Song: *sister* (*achot*, covenant-kinship), *darling* (*rayah*, companion, the one he has chosen), *dove* (*yonah*, purity and gentleness), *perfect one* (*tam*, blameless, whole). He does not approach the door with accusation; he approaches with adoration. His argument for entry is not demand but desire. And the ground he states — *my head is drenched with dew, my locks with the damp of the night* — is an argument from suffering: I have been waiting for you. In the cold. Long enough to be soaked.\n\nThe bride's response in 5:3 is one of Scripture's most honest portraits of self-prioritizing love. She does not say she does not love him; she says she does not want to be inconvenienced. The robe and the feet are petty obstacles — the text intends them to be recognized as petty — yet they function as sufficient barriers against the beloved standing in the cold. This is not the failure of a faithless heart but of a comfortable one. Howard Hendricks noted that the most dangerous spiritual condition is not active rebellion but settled ease; the bride in verse 3 is theology's exhibit A.\n\nThe pivotal turn comes in verse 4. The beloved's hand through the opening (*chor*, the latch-hole) triggers a visceral response: *meeh hamah* — her inmost being thundered, churned, was aroused. *Meeh* in Hebrew refers to the bowels, the viscera, the deep interior — the seat of the most primal emotional responses (cf. Genesis 43:30; Isaiah 63:15; Jeremiah 31:20). Her body responded to his persistence before her will did. She arises, she reaches the door, and she finds myrrh on the bolt — liquid myrrh dripping from the handles. He had anointed the door. He had left his fragrance at the threshold even in her delay.\n\nThe tragedy of 5:6 is the chapter's central event: *I opened to my beloved, but my beloved had turned away and had gone.* The verb *chamaq* (turned away) is rare — used of turning aside, departing; *avar* (gone) suggests he has passed on. He is not hiding; he has left. The bride's soul (*nephesh*) goes out at his departing word — the same *nephesh* that sat comfortable in verse 2 now empties itself in his direction. And the devastating summary: *I sought him but I did not find him; I called him but he did not answer me.* The search is fruitless. The call is unanswered. The door she finally opened now opens onto absence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nephesh* (soul/life-force, 5:6) — the whole animated self, not merely the emotions. *Chamaq* (turned away, departed) appears only here and at 6:5 in the Song; its rarity underlines the singularity of this moment. *Mor avar* (flowing myrrh, 5:5) — *avar* as an adjective means 'passing over, flowing'; the myrrh is liquid, abundant, costly — a gift left at the threshold."
