        "number": 4,
        "title": "The wasf — the portrait that justifies the search (5:10-16)",
        "range": "5:10-16",
        "excerpt": "My beloved is dazzling and ruddy, outstanding among ten thousand... He is wholly desirable. This is my beloved and this is my friend, O daughters of Jerusalem.",
        "body": "The *wasf* of 5:10-16 is the formal literary genre of the ancient Near East — a praise-poem cataloguing the physical features of the beloved from head to foot (or foot to head). Song of Solomon contains three wasfs: 4:1-7 (the bridegroom's praise of the bride), 6:4-7 (the bridegroom again), and 5:10-16 (the bride's praise of the bridegroom — the only wasf spoken by the woman). This is the only example in the Hebrew Bible of a woman describing a man's body in formal literary praise, and it is the most sustained of the three.\n\nThe wasf opens with a summary verdict before the details begin: *dazzling and ruddy* (5:10). *Tsach* = bright, gleaming, radiant; *adom* = ruddy, red — the color of health and vitality (the same word used of David in 1 Samuel 16:12 and 17:42; the Adam-connection to *adamah*/earth is live). He is not pale or wan; he is physically alive. And he is *dagal* — standing out under a banner, conspicuous, identifiable from a distance among ten thousand. The description that follows is the explication of this opening claim.\n\nFrom head to foot: his head is *ketem paz* — purest, most refined gold (5:11); his hair black as a raven (5:11) — the vitality of dark hair against the gold of his head. His eyes are like doves beside streams bathed in milk (5:12) — the same dove-imagery associated with the bride throughout chapters 1-5, now attributed to him; his gaze is characterized by the same purity and gentleness he saw in her. His cheeks are beds of balsam, his lips lilies dripping with myrrh (5:13) — the aromatic fragrances that characterized the garden in 4:12-14 are now attributes of his person. His hands are gold rods set with beryl (5:14); his body carved ivory inlaid with sapphires — the most precious organic material (ivory) and the most precious gem (sapphire, the color of the sapphire throne of God in Exodus 24:10 and Ezekiel 1:26) combined. His legs are alabaster pillars on pedestals of gold (5:15); his bearing like Lebanon, as majestic as its cedars — Lebanon's cedar forests were the ancient world's architectural timber, the material of the Temple itself (1 Kings 5:6-10). The beloved's appearance carries the grandeur of the world's most noble created thing.\n\nThe wasf closes in verse 16 with a move from aesthetics to intimacy: *His mouth is full of sweetness. And he is wholly desirable.* *Machmad* — the object of desire, wholly desirable — is the wasf's summary. And then the sentence that the whole chapter has been building toward: *This is my beloved and this is my friend, O daughters of Jerusalem.* The demonstrative *zeh* (this) is the wasf's signature punctuation: after the full-body description, she names the person she has described. And the double name — *dodi* (my beloved) and *rea* (my friend) — places erotic desire and chosen companionship in the same person without distinction. He is not her lover who happens to be a friend, or her friend with whom she is in love; he is both, simultaneously, exhaustively. This conjunction answers the daughters' question of verse 9 with the only answer adequate to it: the one worth seeking at any cost is the one who is wholly desirable and wholly a friend.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Machmad* (wholly desirable, 5:16) from *chamad* — to desire, to take pleasure in; the same root as the tenth commandment's prohibition of *covetousness* (*lo tachmod*, Exodus 20:17), which shows how native and powerful this human drive is. *Rea* (friend, 5:16) — the covenant-companion word, used of God's friendship with Abraham (Isaiah 41:8; 2 Chronicles 20:7). The pairing *dod/rea* (beloved/friend) in the same person is the Song's definition of covenant love at its fullest."
